sec.p:
Thelepus setosus is well known in Brazil , first identified by Luederwaldt (1929), and subsequently by several researchers, among both formal and unpublished reports (
Amaral et al. 2013
). The original description of T. setosus , however, is very brief and does not mention many characters now considered as important in the taxonomy of the genus. Consequently, T. setosus has been registered worldwide and several authors have later described new species from material initially identified as T. setosus ( Hutchings & Glasby 1987 ; Londoño-Mesa & Carrera-Parra 2005 ; Capa & Hutchings 2006 ; Londoño-Mesa 2009 ). In addition, although subtle, there are consistent differences between the Brazilian specimens and the descriptions of T. setosus available in the literature, and the most recent one was made from material from far from the type-locality ( Hilbig 2000 ). That, together with the geographical distance between the Brazilian coast and the type-locality of T. setosus (Saint Vaast, on the Atlantic coast of France ), made some Brazilian authors prefer to name the Brazilian specimens as T . cf setosus (
Amaral et al. 2013
)
. We examined the holotype of T. setosus to determine if the Brazilian specimens belong to the same species or should be described as a new one, and noticed that the Brazilian specimens not only were different enough from T. setosus to be considered as separate species, but also that two different species occur in the Brazilian waters. These two new species are herein described and a redescription of the holotype of T. setosus is provided.

tp:treatment-sec.p:
Type series. Atlantic Ocean , southeastern Brazil , state of São Paulo , project ‘ BIOTA /FAPESP/ Benthic marine biodiversity in the state of São Paulo’ : Holotype ( MZUSP 3020
) and paratype 7 ( MZUSP 3045
): 25°11.89'S47°08.09'W , 50 m deep, in sand, coll. 16 Dec. 1997 ; paratypes 1–4 (MZUSP 3021, 3022, 3023, 3024, respectively): 23°42'541"S 45°11'380"W, 25.3 m deep, in sand, coll. 29 Jul. 2001 ; paratype 5 (MZUSP 3046): 23°25'663"S 44°46'570"W, 35 m deep, in sand, coll. 11 Jun. 2001 ; paratype 6 (MZUSP 3047): 23°45'062"S 45°13'856"W, 25.3 m deep, in sand, coll. 18 Oct. 2001 . Data on the range of variation of numerical characters within the type series is provided in Table 1 .

